<F P=106> [Article: "Indigenous Newsprint Industry Facing Crisis"] </F>
  [Text] New Delhi, March 7. The Janata Dal member, Mr. 
Sharad Yadav, today drew the attention of the Government in the 
Lok Sabha to the crisis caused in the indigenous newsprint 
industry because of the relaxation in excise duty on foreign 
newsprint. 
  Raising the issue during zero hour, Mr. Yadav said India 
needed 5.5 lakh tonnes of newsprint and it was met by indigenous 
production. Only one lakh tonnes was required from abroad. 
Because of excise duty cuts, about three lakh tonnes of 
newsprint had been imported and that had resulted in stockpiling 
of 40,000 tonnes. 
  Mr. Yadav said that while Rs. 450 crores worth of foreign 
exchange was being spent the inflow had caused distress among 
the indigenous mills. 


