<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> RUSSIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Duma Debates CWC Ratification </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Duma Debates CWC Ratification </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Specialists Speak </H4>

<F P=102> LD2403091994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0831 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2403091994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 24 TASS -- Skilled specialists from 
research institutions and industrial enterprises are taking part 
in today's discussion in the State Duma of Russia's 
participation in international agreements on the destruction of 
chemical weapons. During the discussion they intend to work out 
Russia's political course in the quest for economically 
advantageous and ecologically acceptable ways of disarmament, 
Professor Viktor Kholstov, doctor of chemistry, who took part in 
the discussion, told ITAR-TASS. 
  According to Dr. Kholstov, "the chemical disarmament process 
has a ten-year history. Russia is honestly living up to its 
commitments." He believes, however, that now there is rivalry 
between supporters of two entirely different ways of the 
implementation of the disarmament programme. Some experts 
believe that toxic agents should be destroyed according to 
Western technologies, while others insist on the use of domestic 
technologies, which, by the way, bring in substantial profits 
and ensure ecological safety. 
  According to specialists, major countries of the world have 
become a scene of competition in the sphere of the production 
and sale of super-pure chemical substances, specifically 
arsenic, which is the only chemical element that could be used 
in heleo- installations, capable of replacing all other energy 
sources in the 21st century. American scientists are also 
working hard in this promising field. Fearful of competition, 
Western business people are trying to bar Russian arsenic, 
obtained in the process of the destruction of the toxic agent of 
lewisite, from the world market. According to Russian 
scientists, chemicals produced in Russia, which have a high 
level of purity, can oust products of competitors on the world 
market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-20823 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptac003__l94019" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TAC-94-003-L </AU>
JPRS 
Arms Control 

<DATE1>  24 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> RUSSIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Duma Debates CWC Ratification </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Duma Debates CWC Ratification </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Russia Should `Derive Definite Benefits' </H4>

<F P=102> LD2403150994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1357 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2403150994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 24 TASS -- "There are no toxic agents 
or wastes for a genuine chemist -- they are all raw materials," 
this precept by the great Russian chemist Dmitriy Mendeleyev was 
repeated time and again by scientists, who took the floor during 
the Duma hearings on Russia's participation in international 
agreements to scrap chemical weapons. Believing that Russia 
should derive definite benefits from the destruction of combat 
toxic agents, they moved to include in the state budget a 
separate item, envisaging spendings on disarmament and 
conversion programmes. Moreover, the scientists hold, it is 
necessary to launch a broad explanatory campaign and to discuss 
in a professional way all the problems linked with the 
destruction of weapons. 
  ITAR-TASS was told by Major-General Yuriy Tarasevich, 
assistant commander of radiation, chemical and biological 
defence forces of the Russian Federation, who took part in the 
deliberations, that a concept has already been drawn up for 
scrapping combat toxic substances, but this required special 
financing. Shortage of money for the development of special 
technologies, construction of various installations and other 
jobs, envisaged by the complex programme, retards the 
implementation of the already adopted decisions. 
  General Tarasevich believes that this year will be decisive 
for preparations to begin the planned destruction of chemical 
weapons. He denied rumours and publications on the alleged 
"incineration of chemical shells". "All the ammunition is being 
reliably guarded and poses no threat to the environment," 
Tarasevich said. He believes they could remain stored for 
several more years. "It would be wrong to shift the difficult 
job of destroying them to the next generation. There is every 
opportunity to do it now, relying on international agreements," 
Tarasevich noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

