<H3> <TI>   U.S.-Russian Protocol on Monitoring Russian Uranium Sales </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S.-Russian Protocol on Monitoring Russian Uranium Sales </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Agreement Signed 18 March </H4>

<F P=102> LD1903180794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0248 
GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1903180794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Arkadiy Sidoruk] </F>
  [Text] Washington, 19 Mar -- A document was signed in the 
U.S. capital on 18 March that defines the mechanism for 
monitoring deals involving supplies to the United States of 
Russian Uranium, and its sale on U.S. and world markets, an 
ITAR-TASS correspondent has learned from Russian diplomatic 
sources. 
  The "Protocol on Transparency" concluded by the Russian 
Federation Atomic Energy Ministry and the U.S. Department of 
Energy outlines practical ways to implement the earlier signed 
bilateral agreement between Russia and the United States on 
highly-enriched Russian Uranium extracted from dismantled 
nuclear warheads. It will be degraded and delivered to the 
United States in the form of lowly-enriched Uranium to be sold 
to U.S. and other consumers. 
  A senior Russian diplomat said in a conversation with an 
ITAR-TASS correspondent that the U.S. Government now has 
guarantees that the lowly-enriched Uranium coming from Russia 
has originally been extracted from nuclear warheads. The U.S. 
side is providing the Russian side with guarantees that the 
Russian lowly-enriched Uranium will be used exclusively for 
peaceful ends, not only in the United States, but also in cases 
of its re-export to other countries. 

</TEXT>

